quran[28]{c,v,t,f}:
74,48,"The intercession of the intercessors shall then be of no avail to them. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
74,49,"What is the matter with people that they are turning away from this Exhortation,"
74,50,"as though they were frightened wild asses,"
74,51,"fleeing from a lion? {1}",footnotes:1:This is an idiomatic expression in Arabic which depicts the character of wild donkeys who flee stupefied and stunned as soon as they smell a lion or hear a hunter.
74,52,"No indeed; each one of them desires that open letters be sent to each of them. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
74,53,"No indeed; the truth is that they have no fear of the Hereafter. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
74,54,"Nay; {1} this is an Exhortation.",footnotes:1:That is
74,55,"So, whoever wills may benefit from it."
74,56,"But they will not benefit from it unless Allah Himself so wills. {1} He is worthy to be feared; {2} and He is worthy to forgive (those that fear Him). {3}",footnotes:1:That is
75,1,"Nay, {1} I swear by the Day of Resurrection;",footnotes:1:To begin the discourse with ‘Nay’ by itself indicates that the Surah was sent down to refute some argument which was already in progress. The theme that follows shows that the argument was about Resurrection and life after death
75,2,"and nay, I swear by the self-reproaching soul! {1}",footnotes:1:The Quran has mentioned three kinds of human self:
75,3,"Does man imagine that We will not be able to bring his bones together again? {1}",footnotes:1:The above two arguments
75,4,"Yes indeed; We have the power to remould even his finger-tips. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
75,5,"But man desires to persist in his evil ways. {1}",footnotes:1:In this brief sentence the real disease of the deniers of the Hereafter has been clearly diagnosed. What makes them deny the Hereafter is not
75,6,"He asks: “When will the Day of Resurrection be?” {1}",footnotes:1:This question was not put as a question but derisively and to deny Resurrection
75,7,"When the sight is dazed, {1}",footnotes:1:Literally
75,8,"and the moon is eclipsed,"
75,9,"and the sun and the moon are joined together, {1}",footnotes:1:This is a brief description of the chaotic condition of the system of the universe that will prevail in the first stage of Resurrection. The darkening of the moon and the joining of the moon and the sun together can also mean that not only will the moon lose its light
75,10,"on that Day will man say: “Whither the refuge?”"
75,11,"No, there is no refuge."
75,12,"With your Lord alone will be the retreat that Day."
75,13,"On that Day will man be apprised of his deeds, both the earlier and the later. {1}",footnotes:1:Bima qaddama wa akhkhara is a very comprehensive sentence
75,14,"But lo, man is well aware of himself,"
75,15,"even though he might make up excuses. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
75,16,"(O Prophet), {1} do not stir your tongue hastily (to commit the Revelation to memory).",footnotes:1:The whole passage from here to “Then
75,17,"Surely it is for Us to have you commit it to memory and to recite it."
75,18,"And so when We recite it, {1} follow its recitation attentively;",footnotes:1:Although it was Angel Gabriel who recited the Quran to the Prophet (peace be upon him)
75,19,"then it will be for Us to explain it. {1}",footnotes:1:This gives the feeling
